  "steps": [
    {
      "step": 0,
      "narration": "Let's prove by induction that the sum of the first n natural numbers is n times n plus one over two.",
      "latex": "1 + 2 + 3 + \\ldots + n = \\frac{n(n+1)}{2}",
      "audio_path": "/Users/claudioatlas/Desktop/Orbital/orbital_factory/jobs/b990d88c/audio/step_00.mp3",
      "duration": 6.55
    },
    {
      "step": 1,
      "narration": "First, we'll check the base case where n equals one.",
      "latex": "1 = \\frac{1(1+1)}{2}",
      "audio_path": "/Users/claudioatlas/Desktop/Orbital/orbital_factory/jobs/b990d88c/audio/step_01.mp3",
      "duration": 3.53
    },
    {
      "step": 2,
      "narration": "Simplifying the right side, we get one equals one, which is true.",
      "latex": "1 = 1",
      "audio_path": "/Users/claudioatlas/Desktop/Orbital/orbital_factory/jobs/b990d88c/audio/step_02.mp3",
      "duration": 4.46
    },
    {
      "step": 3,
      "narration": "Now, assume the formula is true for some positive integer k. This is our induction hypothesis.",
      "latex": "1 + 2 + 3 + \\ldots + k = \\frac{k(k+1)}{2}",
      "audio_path": "/Users/claudioatlas/Desktop/Orbital/orbital_factory/jobs/b990d88c/audio/step_03.mp3",
      "duration": 6.69
    },
    {
      "step": 4,
      "narration": "We need to prove it's true for k plus one. So, consider the sum up to k plus one.",
      "latex": "1 + 2 + 3 + \\ldots + k + (k+1)",
      "audio_path": "/Users/claudioatlas/Desktop/Orbital/orbital_factory/jobs/b990d88c/audio/step_04.mp3",
      "duration": 4.69
    },
    {
      "step": 5,
      "narration": "Using our hypothesis, replace the sum up to k with k times k plus one over two.",
      "latex": "\\frac{k(k+1)}{2} + (k+1)",
      "audio_path": "/Users/claudioatlas/Desktop/Orbital/orbital_factory/jobs/b990d88c/audio/step_05.mp3",
      "duration": 6.18
    },
    {
      "step": 6,
      "narration": "Let's combine these terms over a common denominator.",
      "latex": "\\frac{k(k+1) + 2(k+1)}{2}",
      "audio_path": "/Users/claudioatlas/Desktop/Orbital/orbital_factory/jobs/b990d88c/audio/step_06.mp3",
      "duration": 3.16
    },
    {
      "step": 7,
      "narration": "Factor out k plus one from the numerator.",
      "latex": "\\frac{(k+1)(k+2)}{2}",
      "audio_path": "/Users/claudioatlas/Desktop/Orbital/orbital_factory/jobs/b990d88c/audio/step_07.mp3",
      "duration": 2.93
    },
    {
      "step": 8,
      "narration": "This matches the formula for n equals k plus one. So, the formula holds for k plus one.",
      "latex": "\\frac{(k+1)((k+1)+1)}{2}",
      "audio_path": "/Users/claudioatlas/Desktop/Orbital/orbital_factory/jobs/b990d88c/audio/step_08.mp3",
      "duration": 6.32
    },
    {
      "step": 9,
      "narration": "Since both the base case and the induction step are true, the formula is proven for all positive integers n.",
      "latex": "1 + 2 + 3 + \\ldots + n = \\frac{n(n+1)}{2}",
      "audio_path": "/Users/claudioatlas/Desktop/Orbital/orbital_factory/jobs/b990d88c/audio/step_09.mp3",
      "duration": 7.2
    }
  ]
}